<br>
If the story were to go somewhere, I believe the immediate course of action is for him to figure out what's going on.  You should post the main character's goal when trying to introduce a story, otherwise the story has no substance.<br>
<br>
Also I personally dislike the number &quot;666.&quot;  I've been an atheist for four years and it still unnerves me.  Actually makes my forehead itch, actually.  But that's just a personal problem. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#CCCCCC><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/bpolykarbonbbs.showUserPublicProfile?gid=chapel@polykarbonbbs>Chapel</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Karbonite</span><br> <font color=#336699>(2/7/03 5:27:53 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm26.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=925.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> I see your point...</span><hr size=1> I see your point Rakurai, but I'm just giving an overview of the beginnig of the story. It builds, trust me. Here's where it really starts to take shape:<br>
<br>
(Oh, and as for that &quot;666&quot; thing, it's only a pseuodo religious reference. Since that number is associated with evil I used it, he's not like the anti-christ or something. You'll understand what it's for if you read.)<br>
<br>
Voyd<br>
La Part Two<br>
<br>
Upon awakening, Alex finds himself inside the girls apartment, she apparently nursed him back to health. She introduces herself as Mitoko Shumari (Does that sound Japanese enough?). They talk about what happened to Alex for a while, then Mitoko goes to get some food for Alex. In the living room a TV is on to a news program. It turns out that Alex is a wanted man. They say that he is a viscious serial killer. Mitoko is shocked and not sure what to believe. She confronts Alex about this. They come to the conclusion that he was set up by the people that killed his father. They decide it would be safer for Alex to hide out in Mitoko’s apartment until they can find a way to get out of all of this.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp Meanwhile, elsewhere,  Patrick O’Conner (Irish enough?) a bounty hunter whose down on his luck finds a wanted poster of Alex. The reward is $1,000,000 as long as he is alive. In desperate need of the money Patrick decides to go after Alex. Using his investigative skills and various friends in the police, he finds out about the thugs who were attacked by Alex. He finds them and they tell him about the girl. Luckily enough, one of them had swiped her ID and Patrick is able to find out where she lives.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp Meanwhile Alex is sitting around Mitoko’s apartment in deep thought. He’s wondering if he had killed those men who had broken in, maybe he was a murderer. Being so deep in depressing thoughts he doesn’t notice Patrick’s entrance. Patrick places his gun on the back of Alex’s head and tells him to come with him. Alex refuses and tells Patrick to kill him. Patrick, who wants the reward money, promptly refuses. Mitoko returns home and is frightened to find a man holding a gun to Alex’s head. She pleads with him to stop and tells him the story. Patrick turns back to Alex and notices the tattoo on his head. Moving the hair away he is shocked to see the number. He reveals that he has seen similar ones on escaped genetic test subjects from Polymorph Co. (a company which specializes in genetic and cybernetic augmentation). Quincidentally that happens to be the place where Mitoko works as a secretary! The next day at work she breaks in to the file room. She searches to find something about project 666. She finds it on a list titled “Project Voyd”. There are a number of test subjects and pictures in here. Some with “Failure” next to their names others with “Employed” or “Escaped” next to their names.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp All the time Mitoko is out Alex talks to Patrick. Alex asks Patrick if he had ever killed some one. Patrick confesses that he had. There is a big emotional scene as Patrick describes what it was like.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp Mitoko returns with the file. Alex tries to reject this evidence but in the end he sees no other explanation for why his life had been this way. They all decide that it would be best to search for the escapees to see if they know anything about the project, in hopes that they could find out what is going on with Alex.<br>
<br>
